1 0 0 1 56 676.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 658.0 Tm (Abstract) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 644.0 Tm (The familiar red-amber-green traffic signal is often credited to a single inventor, but its) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 630.0 Tm (emergence was a drawn-out negotiation between railway signalling conventions, gas and) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 616.0 Tm (electric lighting technology, and the legal question of who owned the street. This paper) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 602.0 Tm (traces the device from a fatal gas-lit experiment outside the British Parliament in 1868 to) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 588.0 Tm (the standardised electric signal of the interwar years, arguing that the three-colour scheme) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 574.0 Tm (won out for institutional rather than perceptual reasons.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 560.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 542.0 Tm (Introduction) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 528.0 Tm (Every account of the traffic light must reckon with a tempting but misleading question: who) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 514.0 Tm (invented it? The device we use today had no single parent. It was assembled, over roughly) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 500.0 Tm (seventy years, from borrowed parts, and the most interesting of those parts were not) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 486.0 Tm (technical but institutional.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 472.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 458.0 Tm (This paper follows the signal from its first, disastrous appearance to its interwar) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 444.0 Tm (standardisation, paying particular attention to why the now-universal three-colour scheme) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 430.0 Tm (displaced rival arrangements that were, on the evidence available at the time, equally) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 416.0 Tm (plausible.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 402.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 384.0 Tm (The Gas-Lit Prototype) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 370.0 Tm (In 1868 a semaphore signal topped with a gas lantern was erected near the Houses of) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 356.0 Tm (Parliament to manage horse traffic. It borrowed its arms from railway practice and its) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 342.0 Tm (colours, red for stop and green for caution, from the same source. The experiment ended) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 328.0 Tm (within weeks when the gas mechanism exploded and injured the constable operating it.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 314.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 300.0 Tm (The failure is usually treated as a footnote, but it set two lasting precedents. First, it) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 286.0 Tm (established that street signals would inherit the colour vocabulary of the railways rather) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 272.0 Tm (than invent their own. Second, it established that a human operator stood behind the device,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 258.0 Tm (a model that persisted long after the lights themselves became automatic.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 244.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 226.0 Tm (Electrification and the Amber Problem) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 212.0 Tm (Electric signals appeared in American cities in the 1910s, and with them came the central) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 198.0 Tm (dispute of the period: whether a two-state red-green signal sufficed or whether a third,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 184.0 Tm (intermediate state was needed. The intermediate state, amber, had no settled meaning. Some) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 170.0 Tm (cities used it to clear the intersection before a change; others used it as a general) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 156.0 Tm (warning; a few used it to signal that the policeman was about to take manual control.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 142.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 128.0 Tm (The perceptual argument for amber, that drivers needed warning of an imminent stop, was real) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 114.0 Tm (but not decisive. What settled the matter was liability. A clearly defined amber phase) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 100.0 Tm (allowed courts to assign fault in collisions with precision, and municipalities adopted the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 86.0 Tm (three-colour scheme in part to make their intersections legally legible.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 72.0 Tm () Tj
